Spring MVC – 
  Spring MVC is a Java-based web framework built on top of the Spring Framework following the Model-View-Controller (MVC) design pattern.

Configuration Types:
    🔹 XML (Old) - <bean class="DispatcherServlet"/>
    🔹 Java Config
          @Configuration
          @EnableWebMvc
    🔹 Spring Boot (Auto) - No config needed

Core Architecture :
    Client sends HTTP request
    DispatcherServlet (Front Controller) receives it
    It checks HandlerMapping → finds controller method
    HandlerAdapter invokes the controller
    Controller returns:
    View name OR
    Response body (JSON/XML)
    ViewResolver resolves view (JSP/Thymeleaf)
    Response returned to client

Internal Working:
  Client → /user/1
  DispatcherServlet receives request
  Calls: HandlerMapping and Finds correct controller method
  Calls: HandlerAdapter and Controller executes
  Returns: Model + View OR JSON
  DispatcherServlet calls: ViewResolver
  View rendered → Response
  
 Key Components :
 1. DispatcherServlet:
      Central controller of Spring MVC
      Handles all incoming requests
      Defined in web.xml (older) or auto-configured in Spring Boot
      Think of it as:“Traffic police of all requests”
      Without it:
          Every servlet handles its own mapping ❌
          Tight coupling ❌
      With it:
          Centralized routing ✔️
          Loose coupling ✔️
          Easy extensibility ✔️
      DispatcherServlet Lifecycle & Beans:
          🔹 Lifecycle Phases:
              1. Initialization: init()
                  Loads WebApplicationContext
                  Initializes strategies
              2. Request Handling:doDispatch()
              3. Destruction: destroy()
          🔹 Important Internal Beans: DispatcherServlet auto-loads these:
                  Bean	                        Purpose
                  HandlerMapping	              Find controller
                  HandlerAdapter	              Execute controller
                  ViewResolver	                Resolve view
                  HandlerExceptionResolver	    Handle exceptions
                  LocaleResolver	              Localization
                  MultipartResolver	            File upload
           DispatcherServlet uses:Strategy Design Pattern
      How DispatcherServlet is Thread-Safe?
            Key Fact:
                DispatcherServlet is a singleton bean
                Handles multiple requests concurrently (multi-threaded)
            Why it is thread-safe? 
              Because it is stateless
              No request-specific data stored in instance variables
              Uses local variables per request
              doDispatch(HttpServletRequest request, HttpServletResponse response)
            Each request:
              Gets its own thread
              Uses its own stack memory
           Where problems happen?
             In Controller, not DispatcherServlet
              @Controller
              class Test {
                  int count = 0; // ❌ NOT thread-safe
              }
           ✔ Fix:
              Use local variables
              Or ThreadLocal / stateless design  
     How Multiple DispatcherServlets Possible? YES ✔️
          In Configuration , Each DispatcherServlet has:
              Its own ApplicationContext
              Its own Controller set
            Example:
                /api/* → DispatcherServlet1
                /admin/* → DispatcherServlet2
            Use Case:
                Micro frontends
                Modular apps
                Separate admin/user modules
