Filter (Servlet Level): 
    Runs BEFORE DispatcherServlet
    Core Interface :  javax.servlet.Filter (now jakarta.servlet.Filter)
      public interface Filter {
          void init(FilterConfig config);
          void doFilter(ServletRequest req, ServletResponse res, FilterChain chain);
          void destroy();
      }
  Filter Dispatch Types:
      Filters support multiple dispatch types:
        Type	        Meaning
        REQUEST	      Normal request
        FORWARD	      Internal forward
        INCLUDE	      Include another resource
        ASYNC        	Async processing
        ERROR        	Error handling
      Example Flow : REQUEST → FORWARD → ERROR
      Filter may execute multiple times ❌
      ✔ Control Dispatch Types
        registration.setDispatcherTypes(REQUEST, ERROR);
  How Multiple Filters Work?
      Filters are chained - Filter1 → Filter2 → Filter3 → DispatcherServlet
       Execution
        Order defined by:
              @Order
              FilterRegistrationBean
        Flow :Request → F1 → F2 → Controller → F2 → F1 → Response
  Important Filter Implementations (Spring + Servlet):
   1. OncePerRequestFilter:
        Executes only once per request
        Used in JWT, security
       Why do we need it? -> 
          In a normal Servlet Filter, a request may go through multiple dispatch types: REQUEST /FORWARD/ INCLUDE/ASYNC/ERROR
          So the same filter may execute multiple times ❌
        Problem Without OncePerRequestFilter:
          Client → Filter → DispatcherServlet → Forward → Filter again
          Filter runs twice → causes:
              Duplicate logging ❌
              Multiple authentication checks ❌
              Performance issues ❌
       Solution: OncePerRequestFilter. Guarantees: One HTTP request → Filter executes only once
      Internal Working:
        Internally it uses:request.setAttribute("FILTER_APPLIED", true);
        Flow: Check if request already has attribute
                  If YES → skip filter
                  If NO → execute filter and mark it
       Method to Override:
            public class MyFilter extends OncePerRequestFilter {
                @Override
                protected void doFilterInternal(
                    HttpServletRequest request,
                    HttpServletResponse response,
                    FilterChain filterChain)
                    throws ServletException, IOException {
                    System.out.println("Executed once per request");
                    filterChain.doFilter(request, response);
                }
            }
         You DO NOT override doFilter(). You override: doFilterInternal()
    Execution Flow:
          Client Request
             ↓
          OncePerRequestFilter (executes once)
             ↓
          DispatcherServlet
             ↓
          Controller
    Even if: Forward happens/  Async dispatch happens, Filter will NOT run again
        ❗ Async Requests  By default:  shouldNotFilterAsyncDispatch() → true ,So filter may skip async dispatch
        ❗ Error Dispatch - shouldNotFilterErrorDispatch()  Can control behavior
     Real-Time Usage:
         1. JWT Authentication Filter - Validate token once and Set user context
         2. Logging Filter - Log request/response once
         3. Security Filter - Check headers, roles
         4. CORS Handling - Avoid duplicate headers
    When NOT to Use It - Avoid when:
        You need filter for every dispatch
        Low-level servlet control required
   2. GenericFilterBean:
        Spring-friendly base class
        Provides: Bean lifecycle support and Access to Spring context
        Used when: You need Spring features but not once-per-request logic
  3. DelegatingFilterProxy:
        Purpose: Connects Servlet filter → Spring bean
        Filter → DelegatingFilterProxy → Spring Bean (Filter logic)
         Used in:  Spring Security (springSecurityFilterChain)
  4. HttpFilter (Servlet 4+) :Simplified HTTP-specific filter  public abstract class HttpFilter extends GenericFilter
  5. CharacterEncodingFilter (Spring) : Sets request encoding (UTF-8)
  6. HiddenHttpMethodFilter: Converts POST → PUT/DELETE
  7. CorsFilter :Handles CORS headers
  8. FormContentFilter : Parses form data for PUT/PATCH
      Type	                    Purpose
      Authentication Filter    	JWT/Auth
      Logging Filter	          Request logs
      Compression Filter	      GZIP
      CORS Filter	              Cross-origin
      Encoding Filter          	UTF-8
    🔹 Example Flow : Client → Filter → DispatcherServlet → Controller
    🔹 Use Cases:
        Security (JWT)
        Encoding
        Request modification

Interceptor (Spring Level):
   Runs AFTER DispatcherServlet
    public interface HandlerInterceptor {
    boolean preHandle(...)
    void postHandle(...)
    void afterCompletion(...)
      }
  🔹 Methods:
      preHandle()
      postHandle()
      afterCompletion()
  🔹 Flow: Client → DispatcherServlet → Interceptor → Controller
  🔹 Types (based on lifecycle)
        Type	            When
        preHandle	        Before controller
        postHandle	      After controller
        afterCompletion  	After response
  How Multiple Interceptors Work?
       Spring stores: List<HandlerInterceptor>
       Execution Order:
          PreHandle: Interceptor1 → Interceptor2 → Controller
          PostHandle: Controller → Interceptor2 → Interceptor1
          AfterCompletion:Reverse order again
          Order Control:registry.addInterceptor(new MyInterceptor()).order(1);
      Interceptors follow: Chain of Responsibility Pattern
    Special Interceptor Classes:
       1. HandlerInterceptor (Most Used) - Full control over request lifecycle
       2. AsyncHandlerInterceptor -> Extends HandlerInterceptor
              void afterConcurrentHandlingStarted(...)
              Used when: Async requests (@Async, DeferredResult)
       3. HandlerInterceptorAdapter- 
              Old adapter class (now deprecated)
              Previously used to avoid implementing all methods
              Now: Use default methods in interface
       4. WebRequestInterceptor- 
              public interface WebRequestInterceptor {
                  void preHandle(WebRequest request)
                  void postHandle(WebRequest request)
              }
            Difference:Works at WebRequest level, not HttpServletRequest

